# ============================================================================
# Next major version — schema cleanup
# ============================================================================
# Drop transactions.user_id and scheduled_transactions.user_id. They are
# redundant with accounts.user_id (the account owner) and were retained in
# v1.15.0 only to keep many indexes/queries (idx_transactions_user_date,
# idx_transactions_user_sync, sync filters) working without a larger refactor.
# Real attribution lives in created_by_user_id.
#
# To do this safely:
#   1. Migrate every WHERE t.user_id = ? query to filter by account_id IN (...)
#      (most call sites already do this since v1.15.0 — audit the rest).
#   2. Update the Android sync layer to stop relying on user_id as a partition
#      key.
#   3. Drop the indexes that reference user_id, then drop the column.

# ============================================================================
# Scheduled-tx idempotency — defense-in-depth
# ============================================================================
# v1.16.1 fixed the duplicate-materialization race by gating the Android local
# scheduler on sync mode (backend is the sole materializer in webapp mode).
# That closes the dual-execution path, but the schema still has no safeguard
# if a third actor (a future client, a manual API call, a retry) re-materializes
# the same occurrence.
#
# Add a second gate at the schema layer:
#   1. Add scheduled_transaction_id (nullable INTEGER, FK to scheduled_transactions)
#      to the transactions table. Backfill is unnecessary — only new rows set it.
#   2. Add UNIQUE(scheduled_transaction_id, date) WHERE scheduled_transaction_id
#      IS NOT NULL (partial index — SQLite supports it).
#   3. Backend scheduler (scheduler.go) sets the FK on insert.
#   4. Android worker sets the FK on its local insert; sync push includes it.
#   5. POST /api/transactions accepts an optional scheduled_transaction_id and
#      relies on the unique index to reject duplicates with a clear 409.
#   6. Bonus: the scheduled-tx UI can then show "X/Y" derived from
#      COUNT(transactions WHERE scheduled_transaction_id = ?) instead of the
#      brittle counter field, which would self-heal after any past duplication.

